2
00:03:19,580 --> 00:03:20,945
Boys!

3
00:03:32,455 --> 00:03:34,537
I hope you brought your Checkbooks.

4
00:03:56,996 --> 00:03:59,658
The air brakes pay
for George's latest obsession.

5
00:03:59,746 --> 00:04:02,203
By changing the dimensions of his pipes,

6
00:04:02,288 --> 00:04:05,860
George can move natural gas
over 20 miles from the well.

7
00:04:05,955 --> 00:04:07,695
Shooting, like a gun.

8
00:04:07,788 --> 00:04:10,495
Is that good or bad, Mrs. Westinghouse?

9
00:04:11,955 --> 00:04:14,617
- How is your daughter, Gladys?
- Oh, quite well, thank you.

10
00:04:14,705 --> 00:04:16,570
She's met a financier.

11
00:04:16,663 --> 00:04:18,949
The beading on your dress is exquisite.

12
00:04:20,038 --> 00:04:24,361
Mr. Westinghouse, I saw in The World
Mr. Edison's new electric system

13
00:04:24,455 --> 00:04:27,071
is significantly cheaper than gas.

14
00:04:27,163 --> 00:04:29,404
Does that keep you up at night?

15
00:04:29,496 --> 00:04:31,487
There's always more to see.

16
00:04:32,455 --> 00:04:35,162
Mr. and Mrs. Worthington, Mr. Manesberg,

17
00:04:35,246 --> 00:04:38,534
Dr. and Mrs. Burton,
Reverend Vincent, Mr. McCoy,

18
00:04:38,621 --> 00:04:40,907
Mr. Faulk, Miss Faulk, enjoy your evening.

19
00:04:53,871 --> 00:04:57,568
Edison says he's months away
from lighting up the world.

20
00:04:57,663 --> 00:05:01,576
It's impressive, but trust me,
it's ten years away from being practical.

21
00:05:02,663 --> 00:05:05,621
The papers make it sound
as though this is something different.

22
00:05:06,955 --> 00:05:08,320
A miracle.

23
00:05:09,246 --> 00:05:11,862
As if you started to levitate
off the carpet.

24
00:05:13,455 --> 00:05:15,696
I'd love to meet him.
Could you arrange it?

25
00:05:15,788 --> 00:05:17,028
It's been several years...

26
00:05:17,121 --> 00:05:19,362
A dinner.
Comfortable. Elegant. Substantive.

27
00:05:19,455 --> 00:05:23,073
Edison can't be bothered to tie his shoes,
let alone attend a social event.

28
00:05:23,163 --> 00:05:25,950
Perhaps you're right.
But try anyway.

29
00:05:29,538 --> 00:05:31,699
Anything fascinating?

30
00:05:31,788 --> 00:05:35,360
Mr. Pennoyer has found a bargain
on a Beaux Arts shack in Newport.

31
00:05:35,455 --> 00:05:38,492
Mrs. Abernathy's mother has passed,
and apparently Edison believes

32
00:05:38,580 --> 00:05:40,696
it may never be nighttime again.

33
00:05:43,788 --> 00:05:46,120
- Are you excited to meet the President?
- Yes.

34
00:05:46,205 --> 00:05:48,241
Don't say a thing
about JP. Morgan's nose.

35
00:05:48,330 --> 00:05:49,945
- What's wrong with his nose?
- Nothing.

36
00:05:50,038 --> 00:05:53,485
- What's wrong with his nose?
- It's huge. Huge!

37
00:05:53,580 --> 00:05:56,196
It's like someone took a hammer
and slammed it into his face.

38
00:05:56,288 --> 00:05:57,931
I thought you already got the money.

39
00:05:57,955 --> 00:05:59,286
I only got half.

40
00:05:59,371 --> 00:06:00,972
Does Morgan even know
that you're coming?

41
00:06:00,996 --> 00:06:02,861
He'll invest as always. I hate this.

42
00:06:02,955 --> 00:06:04,715
- Mr. Edison, you have dinner with...
- What?

43
00:06:04,788 --> 00:06:06,619
Dinner with Westinghouse. On your return.

44
00:06:06,705 --> 00:06:07,945
Why are barns red?

45
00:06:08,038 --> 00:06:09,722
Maybe so you can
see them in the snow.

46
00:06:09,746 --> 00:06:11,556
- It's 'cause red paint's cheapest.
- What happened to your shoes?

47
00:06:11,580 --> 00:06:13,946
Morgan will want to know
the practicality of your system.

48
00:06:14,038 --> 00:06:15,198
I have money.

49
00:06:15,288 --> 00:06:17,404
Enough for two small buildings
in Manhattan?

50
00:06:17,496 --> 00:06:18,531
Yes.

51
00:06:18,621 --> 00:06:19,656
Oh, good.

52
00:06:33,413 --> 00:06:35,199
This was intended to be my lunch.

53
00:06:35,288 --> 00:06:37,620
The President has asked to see
the phonograph in person.

54
00:06:37,705 --> 00:06:40,538
- I had no idea you'd be here.
- Mrs. Edison.

55
00:06:40,621 --> 00:06:42,236
Mr. Morgan. These are our children.

56
00:06:42,330 --> 00:06:45,037
Dot and Dash. Delightful.
I know what you're doing.

57
00:06:45,121 --> 00:06:48,238
How much are you short? Just how much
of my money do you want to wash away?

58
00:06:48,330 --> 00:06:50,742
Oh, as very, very much as possible.

59
00:06:50,830 --> 00:06:52,536
- Who's this?
- Samuel lnsull.

60
00:06:52,621 --> 00:06:55,283
Mr. Edison's personal secretary.

61
00:06:55,371 --> 00:06:58,693
- Mr. Morgan, Mr. Edison.
- Which one? He's also Mr. Edison.

62
00:06:58,788 --> 00:07:00,494
The President will see you now.

63
00:07:06,913 --> 00:07:08,073
Now.

64
00:07:08,163 --> 00:07:11,405
On top of the Crumpetty Tree
the Quangle Wangle sat,

65
00:07:11,496 --> 00:07:15,159
but his face you could not see,
on account of his beaver hat.

66
00:07:15,788 --> 00:07:17,619
This is the sound of your voice.

67
00:07:20,205 --> 00:07:23,197
On top of the Crumpetty Tree
the Quangle Wangle sat,

68
00:07:23,288 --> 00:07:25,495
but his face you could not see,

69
00:07:25,580 --> 00:07:28,322
- on account of his Beaver Hat.
- Is that what I sound like?

70
00:07:30,205 --> 00:07:32,571
My men tell me
you're turning down $5 million.

71
00:07:32,663 --> 00:07:34,222
I'm grateful for the offer, Mr. President,

72
00:07:34,246 --> 00:07:37,784
but it's the type of science you're after
that I find objectionable.

73
00:07:37,871 --> 00:07:40,264
- There's always money in guns.
- The one device I shall never build

74
00:07:40,288 --> 00:07:42,404
is that which takes the life
of another man.

75
00:07:42,496 --> 00:07:43,611
It's barbaric.

76
00:07:44,830 --> 00:07:47,537
But... take a look at this.

77
00:07:47,621 --> 00:07:50,818
One square mile of Manhattan,
the First District.

78
00:07:50,913 --> 00:07:53,154
- And I'm gonna light it up.
- Then you have done it.

79
00:07:53,246 --> 00:07:55,612
A star in a jar. It's a warm glow.

80
00:07:55,705 --> 00:07:58,993
No smell. No poison.
Thirteen hours of light per globe.

81
00:07:59,080 --> 00:08:00,911
And it's cheaper than gas. Safer too.

82
00:08:00,996 --> 00:08:02,952
We bury the wires using my DC current,

83
00:08:03,038 --> 00:08:06,656
and those same wires
will bring you energy and heat.

84
00:08:07,538 --> 00:08:10,496
I need two buildings to house
six dynamos of my own construction.

85
00:08:10,580 --> 00:08:12,571
This won't even reach my house.

86
00:08:12,663 --> 00:08:15,405
Morgan, let me make you so rich

87
00:08:15,496 --> 00:08:17,389
that you will look back
at this moment and wonder,

88
00:08:17,413 --> 00:08:19,654
"Why was I ever so disgustingly poor?"

89
00:08:22,121 --> 00:08:24,161
It's all right there.
Ferry to Wall Street.

90
00:08:24,246 --> 00:08:26,056
In case you missed my scribble,
that's a big old circle

91
00:08:26,080 --> 00:08:28,116
around the New York Times...
Free advertising.

92
00:08:28,205 --> 00:08:30,321
- One hundred fifty.
- Half a million.

93
00:08:30,413 --> 00:08:33,530
I'm talking about $500,000,
you buy the next century.

94
00:08:34,121 --> 00:08:35,531
Brighter, safer, yours.

95
00:08:35,621 --> 00:08:38,389
Sounds rather grand to me,
Pierpont. If I had your fortune...

96
00:08:38,413 --> 00:08:40,745
With respect, you don't, Mr. President.

97
00:08:44,621 --> 00:08:46,577
- What is that?
- That's not very nice.

98
00:08:46,663 --> 00:08:48,949
Morse code.

99
00:08:49,705 --> 00:08:51,115
What did the boy say?

100
00:08:51,205 --> 00:08:52,639
- What did the boy say?
- If there's nothing else,

101
00:08:52,663 --> 00:08:55,103
- it's been a pleasure, Mr. President.
- What did the boy say?

102
00:08:56,996 --> 00:08:58,657
Do you know what you've done?

103
00:08:59,746 --> 00:09:01,737
I always receive more by saying no.

104
00:09:03,788 --> 00:09:06,825
Set up the Manhattan offices
and make them look professional.

105
00:09:06,913 --> 00:09:08,995
- What does that mean?
- Oh, I don't know. Carpets.

106
00:09:10,371 --> 00:09:12,908
I don't know. Carpets.

107
00:09:12,996 --> 00:09:14,406
And the name?

108
00:09:16,163 --> 00:09:19,485
Edison Electric, of course.
Sir, why not build munitions?

109
00:09:19,580 --> 00:09:21,389
Five million dollars.
It's hard to say no to...

110
00:09:21,413 --> 00:09:23,119
No.

111
00:09:23,205 --> 00:09:24,661
If it's Edison, it works.

112
00:09:24,746 --> 00:09:27,533
If it works,
I'd strongly prefer it not kill anybody.

113
00:09:29,038 --> 00:09:30,118
Right.

114
00:09:59,038 --> 00:10:03,031
Thomas Edison has an unfavorable opinion
of college graduates seeking employment

115
00:10:03,121 --> 00:10:06,193
because they cannot answer
his examination questions.

116
00:10:07,038 --> 00:10:08,744
"Who composed ll Trovatore?"

117
00:10:08,830 --> 00:10:10,161
Verdi.

118
00:10:10,246 --> 00:10:11,966
"What is the speed of sound?"

119
00:10:11,996 --> 00:10:13,139
Oh, a trick question.

120
00:10:13,163 --> 00:10:16,155
Sound travels at
a constantly diminishing rate of speed.

121
00:10:16,246 --> 00:10:21,946
But I believe the fastest rate on record
is 11,463 feet per second.

122
00:10:22,038 --> 00:10:23,699
How do you know all this?

123
00:10:23,788 --> 00:10:25,244
I read that this morning.

124
00:10:29,955 --> 00:10:31,286
This is different.

125
00:10:33,121 --> 00:10:34,611
I can feel it.

126
00:10:35,746 --> 00:10:38,158
You never requested a house guest before.

127
00:10:39,205 --> 00:10:40,285
Really?

128
00:10:42,038 --> 00:10:43,198
Hmm.

129
00:10:50,830 --> 00:10:53,617
- Eight minutes from the junction, sir.
- Hmm?

130
00:10:53,705 --> 00:10:55,445
The Westinghouse dinner.

131
00:10:55,538 --> 00:10:59,326
We're going home. They're tired.
I already shook enough hands today.

132
00:11:02,913 --> 00:11:04,653
Evening, Frank.

133
00:11:04,746 --> 00:11:06,327
George.

134
00:11:07,496 --> 00:11:08,531
Pardon?

135
00:11:09,580 --> 00:11:10,945
I'm not stopping.

136
00:11:12,955 --> 00:11:14,035
Right.

137
00:11:25,996 --> 00:11:27,987
Maybe the brakes are busted.

138
00:11:29,913 --> 00:11:31,528
I doubt that.

139
00:11:57,746 --> 00:11:59,702
An emergency came up in New York.

140
00:12:21,371 --> 00:12:23,236
Don't let him agitate you.

141
00:12:23,996 --> 00:12:25,486
This is how he is.

142
00:12:26,621 --> 00:12:29,454
Before he was a wizard,
I let him live in my basement.

143
00:12:30,413 --> 00:12:33,264
My wife wouldn't have him at the table
with us unless he cleaned himself.

144
00:12:33,288 --> 00:12:35,825
And boy, given the ultimatum,
the man ate alone.

145
00:12:35,913 --> 00:12:37,369
How does he work?

146
00:12:39,455 --> 00:12:42,743
You want to know his secret?
He engineers his own reality,

147
00:12:42,830 --> 00:12:45,196
and he looks for needles in haystacks.

148
00:12:46,121 --> 00:12:48,908
But how does he know
there's a needle in the hay to begin with?

149
00:12:48,996 --> 00:12:50,907
He doesn't. Neither do you.

150
00:12:50,996 --> 00:12:53,612
But he's so determined not to be
the second person to find it,

151
00:12:53,705 --> 00:12:56,287
he'll go stalk by stalk,
on a "what-do-you-know."

152
00:12:56,371 --> 00:12:59,613
He could be the richest man on earth,

153
00:12:59,705 --> 00:13:01,946
but he doesn't give a damn about money.

154
00:13:04,538 --> 00:13:06,779
What does he give a damn about?

155
00:13:10,871 --> 00:13:12,862
Mary? Talk.

156
00:13:12,955 --> 00:13:15,139
- I just want to test the resistance...
- Where's my barrette?

157
00:13:15,163 --> 00:13:17,074
- On top of your bureau.
- What's a bureau?

158
00:13:17,163 --> 00:13:18,949
It's what's under your barrette.

159
00:13:19,038 --> 00:13:22,075
Can I get you to promise on here
that you'll build me a fence?

160
00:13:22,163 --> 00:13:24,404
Ground's frozen. Needs to thaw.

161
00:13:27,288 --> 00:13:28,903
Look, you're missing it!

162
00:13:29,871 --> 00:13:32,283
It's a baby! Still has her spots!

163
00:13:37,871 --> 00:13:39,486
Tom, come see this.

164
00:13:42,621 --> 00:13:45,033
Tom? Tom?

165
00:13:46,621 --> 00:13:49,693
You want half a million dollars,
make me something with your name on it

166
00:13:49,788 --> 00:13:51,824
that I can sell to General Sherman.

167
00:13:51,913 --> 00:13:54,245
Counteroffer.
How about I don't give you what you want,

168
00:13:54,330 --> 00:13:56,070
but you give me everything I want?

169
00:13:59,413 --> 00:14:03,156
We are gonna be big, big, big!

170
00:14:03,246 --> 00:14:06,363
- Bigger than an elephant!
- And no one stops an elephant!

171
00:14:06,455 --> 00:14:08,195
Whoo!

172
00:15:49,413 --> 00:15:50,653
It'll work.

173
00:16:03,455 --> 00:16:06,071
Look, I've got to be honest.
This might not work.

174
00:16:07,996 --> 00:16:11,614
Conventional wisdom has it, if you think
you're gonna fall flat on your face,

175
00:16:11,705 --> 00:16:13,445
better not do it in front of a crowd.

176
00:16:16,871 --> 00:16:19,032
Tonight, things could change.

177
00:16:19,705 --> 00:16:21,570
I hope they do.

178
00:16:22,246 --> 00:16:23,782
And if they do...

179
00:16:25,163 --> 00:16:27,119
they'll change there...

180
00:16:28,121 --> 00:16:29,577
and there.

181
00:16:31,413 --> 00:16:33,825
My boys and I caught in a jar

182
00:16:33,913 --> 00:16:37,235
what before now
has only flashed across the night sky.

183
00:16:38,996 --> 00:16:41,908
What say we unscrew the lid
and see what happens?

184
00:16:41,996 --> 00:16:44,703
You ready?

185
00:16:45,913 --> 00:16:48,950
- Three, two...
- Two, one!

186
00:17:47,371 --> 00:17:51,319
The man has 100,000 feet
of copper for 87 customers.

187
00:17:51,413 --> 00:17:53,404
It will never be profitable.

188
00:17:54,288 --> 00:17:57,610
It's a hobby for the rich.
Something to show off.

189
00:17:57,705 --> 00:17:59,320
It doesn't have to be.

190
00:18:01,788 --> 00:18:05,531
I'm securing patents on the Siemens dynamo
and the Gaulard-Gibbs transformer.

191
00:18:05,621 --> 00:18:08,078
Transformer?
That's more like a metal suitcase.

192
00:18:08,163 --> 00:18:10,529
How much did that cost?

193
00:18:10,621 --> 00:18:13,158
Edison, he picked the wrong horse.

194
00:18:14,163 --> 00:18:16,575
His current is like a hose
with a knot in it.

195
00:18:16,663 --> 00:18:18,699
He needs to sell one generator per mile.

196
00:18:18,788 --> 00:18:22,235
You want to build an AC system.
That's too powerful for motors.

197
00:18:22,330 --> 00:18:25,288
Put doubt out of your mind
for one moment and tell me,

198
00:18:25,371 --> 00:18:27,657
what distance
do you estimate one could get

199
00:18:27,746 --> 00:18:29,577
with a single alternating dynamo?

200
00:18:29,663 --> 00:18:31,119
- A few thousand.
- Yards?

201
00:18:31,205 --> 00:18:32,536
- Miles.
- Mm-hmm.

202
00:18:32,621 --> 00:18:34,953
And how many houses could we reach?

203
00:18:35,038 --> 00:18:37,825
I suppose all of them.
What about the bulbs?

204
00:18:37,913 --> 00:18:39,869
Hiram's agreed to license me his.

205
00:18:39,955 --> 00:18:43,118
If you're gonna rip off Edison,
rip him off right. They glow bright gray.

206
00:18:43,205 --> 00:18:45,912
I just want to do a demonstration
for Edison.

207
00:18:45,996 --> 00:18:48,203
Somewhere small. Small town. Rural.

208
00:18:48,288 --> 00:18:51,780
And then he'll see
alternating is possible,

209
00:18:51,871 --> 00:18:54,237
and we partner... our system, his bulbs.

210
00:18:54,330 --> 00:18:58,494
In my opinion, which I will admit is based
solely on physics and reality,

211
00:18:58,580 --> 00:19:00,741
what you want to do is fun to talk about.

212
00:19:00,830 --> 00:19:02,786
I really don't think it can be done.

213
00:19:02,871 --> 00:19:05,112
- Why?
- Because he would've already done it.

214
00:19:35,580 --> 00:19:39,198
My Paris office seems to think you may be
the only man on Earth to rival me.

215
00:19:39,288 --> 00:19:42,485
- How would you like to work for me?
- Very much.

216
00:19:42,580 --> 00:19:45,868
I'm expanding to 12 cities,
building direct-current systems...

217
00:19:45,955 --> 00:19:47,286
Direct current?

218
00:19:49,496 --> 00:19:51,407
Alternating current is far more efficient.

219
00:19:51,496 --> 00:19:54,078
- Hickory, dickory dock...
- Higher voltage,

220
00:19:54,163 --> 00:19:55,883
greater distance. Less copper conductors...

221
00:19:55,955 --> 00:19:58,947
It's lethal, and it's too much power
for a motor to handle.

222
00:19:59,038 --> 00:20:00,778
I'm going to start you on $100 a month

223
00:20:00,871 --> 00:20:03,362
until you prove yourself worth
more or less.

224
00:20:03,455 --> 00:20:05,639
- A hundred dollars?
- If you can solve five things I can't,

225
00:20:05,663 --> 00:20:08,200
I'll pay you $50,000,
and then I'll have to fire you.

226
00:20:09,205 --> 00:20:11,161
Mr. Tesla, welcome to Edison Electric.

227
00:20:11,246 --> 00:20:13,328
We make a minor invention every ten days

228
00:20:13,413 --> 00:20:15,574
and a major one every six months or so.

229
00:20:19,246 --> 00:20:21,766
I have a suspicion
that though your husband's lab is but

230
00:20:21,830 --> 00:20:25,527
a hundred yards from your house, it must
seem sometimes like a hundred miles.

231
00:20:25,621 --> 00:20:27,111
No, a million.

232
00:20:27,996 --> 00:20:31,363
I've tried to find a way to stop
his brain, but it just runs and runs.

233
00:20:36,163 --> 00:20:39,701
I've heard Mr. Edison called
"the worst husband in America"

234
00:20:39,788 --> 00:20:42,746
on account of him sleeping in his lab
on your wedding night.

235
00:20:42,830 --> 00:20:44,741
I've heard the story myself.

236
00:20:48,580 --> 00:20:50,741
Well, on our wedding night,

237
00:20:50,830 --> 00:20:53,412
Tom and I left on the Albany, uh...

238
00:20:55,163 --> 00:20:56,699
boat.

239
00:20:56,788 --> 00:21:00,201
We spent a week in Niagara Falls.

240
00:21:00,288 --> 00:21:02,495
I thought that one week of happiness
would be enough

241
00:21:02,580 --> 00:21:05,447
to illuminate an entire lifetime.

242
00:21:05,538 --> 00:21:08,575
He was a dashing inventor,
and I worked for him.

243
00:21:08,663 --> 00:21:10,244
You know. I was a...

244
00:21:11,996 --> 00:21:13,657
H was a...

245
