00:39:17,955 --> 00:39:20,446
- Your patents?
- Yes. My patents.

489
00:39:29,705 --> 00:39:31,570
Can I get you anything, sir?

490
00:39:32,830 --> 00:39:34,411
A time machine.

491
00:39:34,913 --> 00:39:38,235
Well, if! Ever find one, I'll travel
back to this moment and give it to you.

492
00:39:39,496 --> 00:39:41,077
Did you read over the proposal?

493
00:39:41,163 --> 00:39:44,826
I'm not diverting what I've got left
of my resources in lighting up a fair.

494
00:39:44,913 --> 00:39:47,529
It's much more than a fair, sir.
A third of this country

495
00:39:47,621 --> 00:39:51,944
will get on trains to Chicago
to try and see this City of Light.

496
00:39:52,455 --> 00:39:54,946
Every window, every streetlamp,
a sign that says,

497
00:39:55,038 --> 00:39:56,903
"The race is over, and we won."

498
00:39:57,663 --> 00:39:59,779
Why spend your final dollars
traveling this country

499
00:39:59,871 --> 00:40:02,453
to show everyone your electricity
when they're all

500
00:40:02,538 --> 00:40:05,029
traveling to the same place
to try to see it anyway?

501
00:40:05,121 --> 00:40:06,639
Because in a year, they'll rip it down.

502
00:40:06,663 --> 00:40:09,279
Only after 30 million people
have seen it, yes.

503
00:40:16,496 --> 00:40:18,282
Westinghouse is placing a bid.

504
00:40:32,830 --> 00:40:35,446
Nice hat. Looks expensive.

505
00:40:35,538 --> 00:40:37,870
I owned this before I worked for you,
Mr. Edison.

506
00:40:37,955 --> 00:40:41,277
I don't think you are working for me.
He's still using my bulbs.

507
00:40:41,371 --> 00:40:43,612
His patents are in order.

508
00:40:43,705 --> 00:40:45,241
Do you want my advice?

509
00:40:45,705 --> 00:40:48,117
You keep saying
Westinghouse's current will kill people,

510
00:40:48,205 --> 00:40:51,402
so in lieu of evidence,
why don't you provide it?

511
00:41:00,705 --> 00:41:04,277
We're doing this because
when we have a complete system,

512
00:41:04,371 --> 00:41:07,534
it works, and it's Edison.

513
00:41:07,621 --> 00:41:09,031
Poor bastard.

514
00:41:09,996 --> 00:41:14,319
Well, he was gonna be slaughtered anyway.
He's not going to feel any pain, right?

515
00:41:14,413 --> 00:41:16,745
At 3,000 volts,
it'll be over before it begins.

516
00:41:16,830 --> 00:41:18,491
So there's nothing to worry about?

517
00:41:19,413 --> 00:41:22,200
But these are reporters, so you might
want to liven up a little bit.

518
00:41:26,788 --> 00:41:29,495
Welcome to Menlo Park.

519
00:41:29,580 --> 00:41:31,866
Thank you for coming out
on this cold morning.

520
00:41:31,955 --> 00:41:34,571
- Good to see you again.
- Good morning.

521
00:41:34,663 --> 00:41:36,699
- I'm Southwick Brown.
- A pleasure.

522
00:41:36,788 --> 00:41:39,245
Now you, uh, you might all
want to stand back a little bit.

523
00:41:39,330 --> 00:41:41,412
Gus is being connected to the same current

524
00:41:41,496 --> 00:41:43,862
that Westinghouse uses from his generator.

525
00:41:43,955 --> 00:41:47,652
But there's no word yet coined
to define death by electricity,

526
00:41:47,746 --> 00:41:50,408
so I asked the men who write
the dictionaries, and I heard back

527
00:41:50,496 --> 00:41:54,068
"electro-dite," "electro-cremate"
and "dyna-mort."

528
00:41:54,163 --> 00:41:58,076
Butjust as Joe Guillotine
got his name on his invention,

529
00:41:58,746 --> 00:42:01,909
how could we rob the rightful inventor
of death by electricity

530
00:42:01,996 --> 00:42:04,282
of his due credit?

531
00:42:04,371 --> 00:42:08,193
I ask you to please be respectful
as we Westinghouse this horse.

532
00:42:38,121 --> 00:42:41,488
Mr. Edison, Southwick Brown,
Capital Punishment Commission.

533
00:42:41,580 --> 00:42:44,617
You've read, no doubt, of the botched
hangings throughout the Northeast.

534
00:42:44,705 --> 00:42:46,972
The prisoners either choke to death...

535
00:42:46,996 --> 00:42:49,032
Or are violently decapitated.

536
00:42:49,121 --> 00:42:50,952
The spectacle is inhumane.

537
00:42:51,038 --> 00:42:54,826
But the horse... his death
was so calm, you could call it...

538
00:42:57,121 --> 00:42:58,531
poetic.

539
00:43:01,788 --> 00:43:05,110
The governor of New York,
upon my personal recommendation,

540
00:43:05,205 --> 00:43:07,287
would like to explore a death device

541
00:43:07,371 --> 00:43:09,862
which uses electricity on a human being.

542
00:43:10,496 --> 00:43:14,034
It would be our honor
to award you the contract.

543
00:43:15,205 --> 00:43:17,662
- If nothing else, a pleasure.
- I beg your pardon?

544
00:43:17,746 --> 00:43:22,160
To kill a human being under the guise
of justice is... is cockeyed.

545
00:43:22,246 --> 00:43:24,703
There's a big difference
between a horse and a person.

546
00:43:24,788 --> 00:43:27,905
God humanely brings us into this world.

547
00:43:28,496 --> 00:43:31,943
Why would you reject the opportunity
to be the first man

548
00:43:32,038 --> 00:43:34,450
to humanely take us out of it?

549
00:44:34,580 --> 00:44:36,036
William.

550
00:44:38,246 --> 00:44:39,907
I killed my wife.

551
00:44:51,788 --> 00:44:53,870
I'm turning the handle.

552
00:44:54,830 --> 00:44:56,741
Maybe there's more to it than that.

553
00:44:57,746 --> 00:45:00,158
If I'm doing it wrong,
you'll never know I was fooling around

554
00:45:00,246 --> 00:45:03,033
with your phonograph or gramophone,

555
00:45:03,121 --> 00:45:05,203
whatever you end up calling it.

556
00:45:05,288 --> 00:45:07,370
And what is this thing really?

557
00:45:08,163 --> 00:45:11,735
Today's Mary is speaking
to tomorrow's Thomas.

558
00:45:11,830 --> 00:45:13,161
Or from where you sit,

559
00:45:13,246 --> 00:45:15,703
today's Tom is listening
to yesterday's Mary.

560
00:45:18,580 --> 00:45:20,946
I wonder what else you can do with it.

561
00:45:29,205 --> 00:45:30,866
Mr. Tesla,

562
00:45:30,955 --> 00:45:33,931
my son and his idiot friend tell me
you don't want to make arc lights anymore.

563
00:45:33,955 --> 00:45:35,491
Is that true?

564
00:45:35,580 --> 00:45:37,992
Don't look at him, look at me.
I'm your primary shareholder.

565
00:45:38,080 --> 00:45:40,617
No. I already completed
the arc light project.

566
00:45:40,705 --> 00:45:44,448
Completed? You covered one city:
Rahway, New Jersey.

567
00:45:44,538 --> 00:45:47,371
For the love of God, think bigger.
Philadelphia.

568
00:45:47,455 --> 00:45:50,572
You design arc lights to outfit cities.
That was your only job.

569
00:45:50,663 --> 00:45:53,735
No. My AC motor. Okay? We agreed...

570
00:45:53,830 --> 00:45:56,321
- No, I never agreed to anything.
- In this office, you said...

571
00:45:56,413 --> 00:45:57,528
Uh!

572
00:45:57,621 --> 00:45:59,953
Lane, could you wait outside for a moment?

573
00:46:06,871 --> 00:46:09,362
I'm sorry. Don't you realize
you're being fired here?

574
00:46:11,496 --> 00:46:15,284
No. Please, let me work through
what I have in my head.

575
00:46:15,371 --> 00:46:18,534
I will make you the greatest provider
of electrical power in the world.

576
00:46:18,621 --> 00:46:20,407
Better than Edison.

577
00:46:20,496 --> 00:46:22,828
I'm-I'm so close. Just a few months.

578
00:46:27,538 --> 00:46:30,325
You drop in here like you're from Neptune,

579
00:46:30,413 --> 00:46:33,155
like you got a great vision of the future

580
00:46:33,246 --> 00:46:35,347
- that no one understands but you.
- No, please don't touch.

581
00:46:35,371 --> 00:46:37,407
But you're just an immigrant.

582
00:46:38,246 --> 00:46:41,204
Head full of notions,
looking for a handout. You're not Edison.

583
00:46:41,288 --> 00:46:44,405
There's only one Edison. That's why
he's in. There's millions of you.

584
00:46:44,496 --> 00:46:48,614
Big ideas, but you can't see
the real force that moves things.

585
00:46:48,705 --> 00:46:51,663
And it's not AC/DC, it's not currents.

586
00:46:52,330 --> 00:46:53,695
It's currency.

587
00:46:54,288 --> 00:46:56,370
And that's the only motor
I'm interested in.

588
00:46:59,496 --> 00:47:03,239
These patents belong to
the Tesla Electric Light Company.

589
00:47:03,330 --> 00:47:06,902
This is now the Union Electric
and Manufacturing Company,

590
00:47:06,996 --> 00:47:09,032
and I own everything in this office.

591
00:47:09,663 --> 00:47:12,985
Patents, designs, engineers, all mine.

592
00:47:14,246 --> 00:47:16,908
Never going to be anything
named Tesla ever again.

593
00:47:18,288 --> 00:47:22,486
You take your notions
and go back where you came from.

594
00:47:34,996 --> 00:47:36,987
He's snapping up town after town.

595
00:47:37,955 --> 00:47:41,493
Cats, dogs, sheep, 11 horses...
What more do people need to see?

596
00:47:41,580 --> 00:47:43,992
The problem is, no one's actually dying
from alternating,

597
00:47:44,080 --> 00:47:47,038
apart from your cats,
dogs, sheep and 11 horses.

598
00:47:48,330 --> 00:47:51,037
- Sir, I realize I'm only your secretary...
- Just say it.

599
00:47:51,121 --> 00:47:53,988
Bring the phonograph to market.
You can make your own money.

600
00:47:54,080 --> 00:47:56,787
- No, it needs too many improvements.
- Make them. Sir.

601
00:47:57,830 --> 00:48:00,822
- Bell is ripping you off.
- Graphophone? He just switched the name.

602
00:48:00,913 --> 00:48:03,889
Direct me to a store where I can buy
yours, and I won't give him the business.

603
00:48:03,913 --> 00:48:06,029
You have a real offer on the table here.

604
00:48:06,705 --> 00:48:09,993
Half a million dollars.
Sir, take the money. You need it.

605
00:48:11,121 --> 00:48:13,112
If Bell ripped you off with the telephone,

606
00:48:13,205 --> 00:48:15,196
he'll do it again with the graphophone.

607
00:48:15,288 --> 00:48:17,449
Did you just misspeak intentionally?

608
00:48:17,538 --> 00:48:19,529
Do you want Chicago?

609
00:48:23,913 --> 00:48:25,403
All right, I'm ready.

610
00:48:46,621 --> 00:48:47,986
A dollar a ball?

611
00:48:48,788 --> 00:48:50,449
So, what's your trade?

612
00:48:50,538 --> 00:48:53,860
Inventor. I fix problems for idiots.

613
00:48:54,955 --> 00:48:58,027
Imagine dictation
without the aid of a stenographer.

614
00:48:59,788 --> 00:49:02,655
Phonographic books
that will speak to blind people.

615
00:49:02,746 --> 00:49:05,328
Reproduction of music. Talking toys.

616
00:49:05,830 --> 00:49:08,663
Clocks that will announce the time.

617
00:49:08,746 --> 00:49:10,987
The preservation of dying languages.

618
00:49:11,080 --> 00:49:12,945
Teaching of elocution.

619
00:49:13,038 --> 00:49:15,575
- You hustled us.
- Yes. No.

620
00:49:16,496 --> 00:49:17,889
I didn't come all this way to lose.

621
00:49:17,913 --> 00:49:21,235
The final capturing of the dying words
of your loved ones.

622
00:49:25,163 --> 00:49:28,235
Mary had a little lamb,
his fleece was white as snow,

623
00:49:28,330 --> 00:49:31,447
and everywhere that Mary went,
the lamb was sure to go.

624
00:49:37,371 --> 00:49:41,660
Well, it's either not possible,
or I'm not the engineer I thought I was.

625
00:49:43,871 --> 00:49:47,409
And he's traveling around the country,
cooking up cats.

626
00:49:47,496 --> 00:49:50,533
George, he's playing dirty. You can too.

627
00:49:50,621 --> 00:49:51,656
Mm.

628
00:49:53,288 --> 00:49:55,745
You know, when I was a boy, my father...

629
00:49:56,996 --> 00:49:58,987
tried to whip me with a branch.

630
00:50:00,038 --> 00:50:03,951
But after the first hit,
it broke into three little pieces.

631
00:50:05,580 --> 00:50:08,902
And we just stood there, looking at
this shattered stick on the ground.

632
00:50:10,538 --> 00:50:14,076
And then I noticed there was
a leather strap hanging on the wall,

633
00:50:14,163 --> 00:50:16,370
so I pointed to it and said,

634
00:50:16,455 --> 00:50:19,868
"Look. That's the better one."

635
00:50:21,080 --> 00:50:22,536
And he stopped.

636
00:50:27,038 --> 00:50:31,702
I can take a beating, but I have
no patience for shoddy craftsmanship.

637
00:50:34,330 --> 00:50:38,118
You are gonna have a working motor
sitting next to your display in Chicago,

638
00:50:38,205 --> 00:50:41,447
come hell, high water,
or the Wizard of Menlo Park.

639
00:50:48,205 --> 00:50:49,911
- Good night, Frank.
- Good night.

640
00:51:49,038 --> 00:51:51,029
So you admit Edison was right?

641
00:52:19,538 --> 00:52:21,824
We will remember Franklin Pope...

642
00:52:22,746 --> 00:52:25,533
for his fearless dedication
to moving us fonrvard.

643
00:52:26,288 --> 00:52:29,405
He tried to see
what was hiding in plain sight.

644
00:52:35,163 --> 00:52:36,824
Today, I am...

645
00:52:38,663 --> 00:52:40,619
filled less with grief than anger,

646
00:52:40,705 --> 00:52:43,162
because what happened
could've been avoided.

647
00:52:45,580 --> 00:52:48,447
Hear me now
as you have never heard me before.

648
00:52:49,288 --> 00:52:50,869
As I breathe...

649
00:52:52,455 --> 00:52:54,616
as long as Westinghouse
stays in business...

650
00:52:56,038 --> 00:52:58,074
more people will die.

651
00:53:18,205 --> 00:53:19,945
My condolences.

652
00:53:22,288 --> 00:53:24,745
Sounds like he was
more than just an employee.

653
00:53:29,830 --> 00:53:32,037
What was his name? Franklin Popes?

654
00:53:33,205 --> 00:53:35,287
Pope. Just one.

655
00:53:36,538 --> 00:53:38,620
- It's a shame.
- Mm.

656
00:53:38,705 --> 00:53:40,241
But I'm here to help.

657
00:53:40,996 --> 00:53:42,861
Now, I know that you, uh,

658
00:53:42,955 --> 00:53:44,991
you wish Edison to quiet down.

659
00:53:47,746 --> 00:53:51,238
So let me combine your companies.
Let me clean up the mess.

660
00:53:55,205 --> 00:53:59,027
You really think Westinghouse Electric
is worth $5 million?

661
00:53:59,121 --> 00:54:02,409
The value of something is the highest
number someone else is willing to pay.

662
00:54:02,496 --> 00:54:06,068
But 800 men will lose their livelihoods.

663
00:54:06,163 --> 00:54:08,324
I will keep your workers.

664
00:54:08,413 --> 00:54:11,951
I will not make the same promise
for your five-day work week.

665
00:54:12,038 --> 00:54:13,073
Mm.

666
00:54:14,580 --> 00:54:16,662
Seems like you're amenable.

667
00:54:19,330 --> 00:54:20,410
Mm.

668
00:54:27,330 --> 00:54:29,286
Which current will you use?

669
00:54:30,788 --> 00:54:33,029
Whichever Edison selects, I suppose.

670
00:54:42,913 --> 00:54:44,244
Absurdity.

671
00:54:44,871 --> 00:54:46,782
You think I'm being absurd?

672
00:54:47,955 --> 00:54:49,820
Yes, I do.

673
00:54:49,913 --> 00:54:52,120
We're overextended, Marguerite.

674
00:54:53,246 --> 00:54:55,157
There's no shame in selling.

675
00:54:59,038 --> 00:55:02,201
What I was always after
was to partner with Edison...

676
00:55:03,246 --> 00:55:05,328
and I have the chance to do that now.

677
00:55:06,538 --> 00:55:10,486
We have no motor, so we're a train into
a mountainside anyway. It's impossible.

678
00:55:10,580 --> 00:55:13,617
I thought "impossible" wasn't a word
in your vocabulary.

679
00:55:19,746 --> 00:55:21,782
I am dissolving Westinghouse Electric.

680
00:55:21,871 --> 00:55:26,069
The proceeds will go to preserve
our other failing enterprises,

681
00:55:26,163 --> 00:55:30,236
and time itself will mend
Edison's mistakes.

682
00:55:30,330 --> 00:55:34,278
You are not a captain
who changes his course with the sea.

683
00:55:34,371 --> 00:55:36,282
We are not on a course!

684
00:55:36,871 --> 00:55:38,702
We're drowning!

685
00:55:38,788 --> 00:55:41,700
This whole thing is costing us a fortune!

686
00:55:41,788 --> 00:55:44,325
- You don't care about money.
- A fortune!

687
00:55:45,663 --> 00:55:48,826
I lived in your parents' house
while you went door-to-door.

688
00:55:49,455 --> 00:55:52,527
Do you want people saying
you stand for everything you don't?

689
00:55:52,621 --> 00:55:54,703
Using your last name as a verb?

690
00:55:54,788 --> 00:55:58,076
Well, how exactly do you suggest
I correct that, dear?

691
00:55:59,538 --> 00:56:02,655
I have you, and I had Frank.

692
00:56:04,246 --> 00:56:05,326
That's it.

693
00:56:06,580 --> 00:56:08,161
I loved the man.

694
00:56:09,955 --> 00:56:14,369
This is really nothing
but a sensible business decision.

695
00:56:15,788 --> 00:56:17,824
- George...
- That's all.

696
00:56:22,413 --> 00:56:23,653
That's all.

697
00:56:30,371 --> 00:56:33,283
Say what you will about
George Westinghouse, he sure is nice.

698
00:57:09,288 --> 00:57:12,530
You've crossed into territory
for the Confederacy.

699
00:57:14,538 --> 00:57:17,575
No, I, uh, I think you're mistaken.

700
00:57:18,121 --> 00:57:20,407
According to my map here...

701
00:57:31,580 --> 00:57:36,244
Though I mourn the loss of my colleague,
misfortune does not trump progress.

702
00:57:38,455 --> 00:57:42,778
Now, it seems to me that Mr. Edison
puts his name on everything

703
00:57:42,871 --> 00:57:45,783
because he's terrified of being forgotten.

704
00:57:46,955 --> 00:57:49,947
IF YOU WANT TO BE REMEMBERED, IT'S SIMPLE:
Shoot a president.

705
00:57:50,913 --> 00:57:54,076
But if you prefer to have
what I call a legacy,

706
00:57:54,163 --> 00:57:57,030
you leave the world
a better place than you found it.

707
00:57:58,080 --> 00:58:01,402
Thomas Alva Edison is a charlatan

708
00:58:01,496 --> 00:58:05,159
who preys on the fears of the common man

709
00:58:05,246 --> 00:58:07,362
because I have the better system.

710
00:58:08,788 --> 00:58:13,862
And because I do have the better system,
Westinghouse Electric shall endure.

711
00:58:13,955 --> 00:58:15,035
Good day.

712
00:58:16,288 --> 00:58:19,735
Westinghouse has taken the lead.
He's not going away.

713
00:58:19,830 --> 00:58:23,573
And while I appreciate your lights,
Mr. Edison, I'm also your customer.

714
00:58:24,163 --> 00:58:26,905
If something comes to my door
and offers me something that I need

715
00:58:26,996 --> 00:58:30,159
that is better than what I have now,
at a cheaper price,

716
00:58:30,246 --> 00:58:33,318
why, I'd be a tool
not to invite him in for tea.

717
00:58:33,413 --> 00:58:36,325
- Is this an ultimatum?
- More of a threat.

718
00:58:36,413 --> 00:58:38,449
If you maintain
that fear is the best strategy,

719
00:58:38,538 --> 00:58:40,620
then you'd better hurry up and try harder.

720
00:58:42,205 --> 00:58:43,240
Time's up.

721
00:58:46,830 --> 00:58:48,912
Man who was handsome and clever

722
00:58:48,996 --> 00:58:51,487
built a box with a crank and a lever

723
00:58:51,580 --> 00:58:55,072
to store his wife's voice,
though he made a poor choice,

724
00:58:55,163 --> 00:58:58,826
because now she can tease him forever.

725
00:59:01,288 --> 00:59:04,701
I couldn't stop it if I wanted to,

726
00:59:05,205 --> 00:59:06,945
which I don't,

727
00:59:07,038 --> 00:59:10,485
because I...
I think it's a remarkable gift.

728
00:59:11,955 --> 00:59:15,868
Electricity will kill that man in Buffalo.

729
00:59:15,955 --> 00:59:18,742
We don't know the voltage.

730
00:59:18,830 --> 00:59:22,527
Too much, and he ignites.
Too little, and he's still alive.

731
00:59:23,121 --> 00:59:25,487
All we need is your advice.

732
00:59:25,580 --> 00:59:28,947
How much is humane?
Where to put the electrode?

733
00:59:29,038 --> 00:59:33,907
And in exchange, I will promise you
something that I know you want.

734
00:59:35,913 --> 00:59:40,236
I will put the Westinghouse name
right out front

735
00:59:40,330 --> 00:59:44,278
as the official electricity used
to kill human beings.

736
00:59:46,663 --> 00:59:50,656
I even think we can get this chair
on display at the Chicago World's Fair.

737
00:59:52,371 --> 00:59:54,032
The future.

738
01:00:02,038 --> 01:00:04,120
My name must never be
associated with this.

739
01:00:04,205 --> 01:00:07,038
I did not provide any consultation,
and you will advertise

740
01:00:07,121 --> 01:00:10,079
that Westinghouse is the best way
to take a human life.

741
01:00:11,163 --> 01:00:12,824
You guarantee your assistance?

742
01:00:14,788 --> 01:00:17,154
You ask a question, and I'll reply.

743
01:00:20,871 --> 01:00:22,452
Burn the correspondence.

744
01:00:23,913 --> 01:00:25,449
Absolutely.

745
01:00:28,621 --> 01:00:31,943
Fauteuils and blue painted bergere.

746
01:00:32,038 --> 01:00:34,370
I sold three sets of these
last week alone.

747
01:00:36,746 --> 01:00:39,533
Oh, uh, this is your classic spindle back.

748
01:00:39,621 --> 01:00:42,533
Oh, yes. And these are framed cockpen.

749
01:00:42,621 --> 01:00:44,282
Quite popular.

750
01:00:50,621 --> 01:00:52,703
Oh, deportment style.

751
01:00:55,538 --> 01:00:58,371
Would you like four, six, eight, 12?

752
01:00:58,455 --> 01:00:59,490
Just one.

753
01:01:01,246 --> 01:01:05,114
Mr. Brown, the apparatus
consists of a stationary engine,

754
01:01:05,205 --> 01:01:09,027
a Westinghouse alternating dynamo
capable of generating 3, 000 volts,

755
01:01:09,121 --> 01:01:12,534
wood chair with headrest,
binding straps and adjustable electrodes.

756
01:01:12,621 --> 01:01:14,828
Burn. TAE.

757
01:01:23,330 --> 01:01:25,821
The voltmeter, ammeter
and switchboard controlling the current

758
01:01:25,913 --> 01:01:28,905
should be located in the execution room
for monitoring.

759
01:01:28,996 --> 01:01:30,577
Burn. TAE.

760
01:01:30,663 --> 01:01:34,110
The dynamo room is communicated
by electric signals. Burn. TAE.

761
01:01:34,205 --> 01:01:37,652
The most effective machines manufactured
by Westinghouse... Burn. TAE.

762
01:01:37,746 --> 01:01:41,819
I authorize payment of $3, 600
for your efforts.

763
01:01:41,913 --> 01:01:43,528
Burn. TAE.

764
01:01:43,621 --> 01:01:46,738
The only argument which can be
urged against "Westinghousing"

765
01:01:46,830 --> 01:01:48,912
on the score of cruel punishment is that

766
01:01:48,996 --> 01:01:51,112
the flesh may burn
at the points of contact,

767
01:01:51,205 --> 01:01:53,885
and the amount of current which can be
given without such mutilation

768
01:01:53,955 --> 01:01:55,820
is not yet known.

769
01:01:55,913 --> 01:01:58,154
Burn. TAE.

770
01:02:08,371 --> 01:02:10,611
For someone who's trying to compete
for the World's Fair,

771
01:02:10,663 --> 01:02:12,369
this death-trap business
doesn't look good.

772
01:02:12,455 --> 01:02:16,698
Yeah, I know. It's just Edison
trying to smear me, as usual.

773
01:02:16,788 --> 01:02:18,699
- Can you prove it?
- No.

774
01:02:18,788 --> 01:02:21,245
But I was thinking maybe I could stop it.

775
01:02:22,038 --> 01:02:23,403
You mean me?

776
01:02:24,538 --> 01:02:27,655
You want my advice?
Don't hire me. Save your money.

777
01:02:28,663 --> 01:02:31,905
But I do know a man who could determine

778
01:02:31,996 --> 01:02:35,238
whether Edison has an exploitable
connection with the death chair.

779
01:02:35,330 --> 01:02:38,697
No, I was thinking
we could stop him via legal means.

780
01:02:39,955 --> 01:02:42,412
- You want me to put Edison on trial?
- No.

781
01:02:42,496 --> 01:02:44,828
The chair itself. The Eighth Amendment.

782
01:02:44,913 --> 01:02:47,370
So I'm to get an ax murderer

783
01:02:47,455 --> 01:02:49,992
who readily admits he slaughtered his wife

784
01:02:50,080 --> 01:02:51,911
a what... a sustainment?

785
01:02:51,996 --> 01:02:53,827
This is about showing,

786
01:02:53,913 --> 01:02:56,655
what kind of a man is Thomas Edison?

787
01:02:58,663 --> 01:03:00,779
You just keep my name out of it.

788
01:03:00,871 --> 01:03:03,078
Does your wife know
you're paying for this?

789
01:03:03,163 --> 01:03:04,994
It was her idea.

790
01:03:08,496 --> 01:03:11,909
What precisely makes electricity
not cruel and not inhumane?

791
01:03:11,996 --> 01:03:14,032
The velocity of the current is so great

792
01:03:14,121 --> 01:03:17,158
that the brain
is instantaneously paralyzed.

793
01:03:17,246 --> 01:03:18,952
The subject is dead

794
01:03:19,038 --> 01:03:21,654
before the nerves
can communicate any shock.

795
01:03:21,746 --> 01:03:23,611
How can you know if you haven't proof?

796
01:03:23,705 --> 01:03:24,990
I tested it...

797
01:03:25,746 --> 01:03:27,953
on a gorilla from London Zoo.

798
01:03:28,038 --> 01:03:31,576
Are you connected in any way with
any of the electric lighting companies?

799
01:03:31,663 --> 01:03:33,199
No, sir.

800
01:03:33,288 --> 01:03:36,860
The State calls Thomas Alva Edison.

801
01:03:36,955 --> 01:03:39,367
Will you explain generally

802
01:03:39,455 --> 01:03:41,946
the difference between
your continuous current

803
01:03:42,038 --> 01:03:45,735
and Mr. Westinghouse's
alternating electricity?

804
01:03:46,330 --> 01:03:49,572
A continuous current flows
like water through a pipe,

805
01:03:49,663 --> 01:03:51,870
and alternating current flows
in both directions.

806
01:03:51,955 --> 01:03:53,820
Water. That doesn't sound so dangerous.

807
01:03:53,913 --> 01:03:55,778
Not until you drown.

808
01:03:55,871 --> 01:03:58,658
Why don't you use
Mr. Westinghouse's current?

809
01:03:58,746 --> 01:04:01,078
- I don't like it.
- You think it's dangerous.

810
01:04:01,163 --> 01:04:02,369
Yes, I do.

811
01:04:02,455 --> 01:04:04,696
Suppose you took this...

812
01:04:05,746 --> 01:04:08,158
wicked Westinghouse current...

813
01:04:08,246 --> 01:04:10,988
the one that is going to be used
on Mr. Kemmler here...

814
01:04:11,955 --> 01:04:15,118
now, suppose you kept it up
for five or six minutes.

815
01:04:15,913 --> 01:04:18,370
At 1,500 volts,

816
01:04:18,455 --> 01:04:20,946
how long would it take
before he would feel the heat?

817
01:04:21,038 --> 01:04:24,155
Well, the temperature might rise

818
01:04:24,246 --> 01:04:26,282
four or five degrees above normal

819
01:04:26,371 --> 01:04:29,078
and continue until he was mummified.

820
01:04:29,830 --> 01:04:32,196
And this wouldn't cause considerable pain?

821
01:04:32,288 --> 01:04:33,949
- It would not.
- How do you know?

822
01:04:34,038 --> 01:04:36,404
Because I personally observed
such electricity

823
01:04:36,496 --> 01:04:38,532
being used to execute
a thousand-pound horse.

824
01:04:38,621 --> 01:04:41,181
- And did the horse feel pain?
- If he did, he didn't mention it.

825
01:04:43,830 --> 01:04:46,287
Now, Mr. Edison,
there is a great degree of feeling

826
01:04:46,371 --> 01:04:48,362
between you and Mr. Westinghouse.

827
01:04:48,455 --> 01:04:51,288
I do not dislike Mr. Westinghouse.

828
01:04:51,371 --> 01:04:53,491
There is a contest
between you two, isn't there?

829
01:04:53,580 --> 01:04:55,536
That is not what this is about.

830
01:04:56,746 --> 01:04:58,907
I've been asked
as a dispassionate scientist

831
01:04:58,996 --> 01:05:02,033
to advise on the simple question
of whether death by electricity

832
01:05:02,121 --> 01:05:04,908
is a violation of the Eighth Amendment
and is cruel and unusual.

833
01:05:04,996 --> 01:05:08,318
In my expert opinion,
the only humane method of execution

834
01:05:08,413 --> 01:05:10,404
is Westinghouse alternating current.

835
01:05:10,496 --> 01:05:12,847
Your Honor, Mr. Edison knows
that any current over 30 amperes...

836
01:05:12,871 --> 01:05:16,409
Milliamperes. If you're gonna interrupt,
do so in the proper denominations.

837
01:05:18,996 --> 01:05:20,452
Oh, thank you, Your Honor.

838
01:05:20,538 --> 01:05:22,014
It's my honor.

839
01:05:22,038 --> 01:05:24,370
All right, that's all I need to hear.

840
01:05:35,371 --> 01:05:37,532
What do you two lowlifes want, huh?

841
01:05:37,621 --> 01:05:39,486
Mr. Edison. Mr. Edison.

842
01:05:39,580 --> 01:05:40,615
Huh?

843
01:05:43,871 --> 01:05:45,031
Now look...

844
01:05:45,121 --> 01:05:47,014
I thought you were gonna leave
before I had a chance.

845
01:05:47,038 --> 01:05:50,701
- Mr. Edison, can I get your autograph?
- Uh, yeah, sure, I...

846
01:05:50,788 --> 01:05:52,779
William, do you mind?

847
01:06:03,663 --> 01:06:07,030
I should warn you, there's one thing
that always beats justice.

848
01:06:07,121 --> 01:06:08,236
Money?

849
01:06:08,330 --> 01:06:09,365
Fame.

850
01:06:30,496 --> 01:06:32,987
Oh, is that a New Model Army revolver?

851
01:06:33,663 --> 01:06:35,904
What a lovely machine that is.

852
01:06:36,830 --> 01:06:39,287
- Do you know how it works?
- You want me to show you?

853
01:06:39,371 --> 01:06:42,909
Oh, I didn't mean how it fires.
I simply meant how it works.

854
01:06:43,663 --> 01:06:46,120
It's quite a device.
You should have a look.

855
01:06:46,205 --> 01:06:49,447
You see, they designed the cylinder
so the hammer

856
01:06:49,538 --> 01:06:51,904
doesn't have to sit in an empty chamber.

857
01:06:51,996 --> 01:06:54,863
So I could shoot you six times
instead of five.

858
01:06:54,955 --> 01:06:57,742
Well, I suppose.

859
01:06:59,205 --> 01:07:01,412
They both lied on the stand.

860
01:07:02,330 --> 01:07:05,902
If you're gonna take your shot,
now is the last time to fire.

861
01:07:05,996 --> 01:07:09,193
Sometimes we have to work
outside of the rules to get what's right.

862
01:07:11,205 --> 01:07:13,196
It would be nice if we didn't have to.

863
01:07:14,913 --> 01:07:15,993
Wouldn't it?

864
01:07:17,246 --> 01:07:19,862
- This doesn't make you like him.
- Mm.

865
01:07:22,830 --> 01:07:24,240
So, what will it be?

866
01:08:22,413 --> 01:08:24,904
In my bad ear, it sounded extraordinary.

867
01:08:24,996 --> 01:08:26,156
Father...

868
01:08:29,705 --> 01:08:30,740
Hello.

869
01:08:30,830 --> 01:08:33,663
The apparatus consists
of a stationary engine,

870
01:08:33,746 --> 01:08:36,203
a Westinghouse alternating dynamo

871
01:08:36,288 --> 01:08:38,745
capable of generating 3, 000 volts.

872
01:08:38,830 --> 01:08:40,866
Wood chair with headrest,

873
01:08:40,955 --> 01:08:43,742
- Where did you get that?
- I'm sending them to the paper.

874
01:08:43,830 --> 01:08:46,902
Those letters are stolen.
You can't publish them.

875
01:08:46,996 --> 01:08:49,453
- Why not?
- Because they're private correspondences.

876
01:08:49,538 --> 01:08:53,326
Mr. Edison, if you say something
about me or my company again,

877
01:08:53,413 --> 01:08:55,574
I would ask that you tell the truth.

878
01:08:57,121 --> 01:08:59,453
That would be the decent thing to do.

879
01:09:01,413 --> 01:09:02,528
Wouldn't it?

880
01:09:04,913 --> 01:09:08,610
- Why didn't you burn the letters?
- They were from Thomas Edison.

881
01:09:08,705 --> 01:09:11,492
I don't think you appreciate
that this chair is something

882
01:09:11,580 --> 01:09:13,821
to be proud of and remembered for.

883
01:09:13,913 --> 01:09:16,199
I don't even know
how much electricity you need to use.

884
01:09:16,288 --> 01:09:19,906
- You said 1,500 volts.
- I said I think 1,500 volts.

885
01:09:19,996 --> 01:09:22,658
But if all the water in his body
evaporates, then he may ignite.

886
01:09:22,746 --> 01:09:25,453
- So we lower the amount.
- Then you slowly roast him to death.

887
01:09:25,538 --> 01:09:29,076
Listen. You must listen to me.
What you're going to do is wrong.

888
01:09:29,163 --> 01:09:31,950
Now you said that it's inevitable
and somebody else will do it.

889
01:09:32,038 --> 01:09:35,280
But just because somebody else is
gonna do it doesn't mean that you have to.

890
01:09:36,330 --> 01:09:40,528
The State thanks you
for your expert opinion and your help.

891
01:10:00,038 --> 01:10:01,118
What?

892
01:10:04,121 --> 01:10:06,203
- It's not my place to say.
- Say it.

893
01:10:06,955 --> 01:10:09,662
You said you'd never build
a device that would kill anyone.

894
01:10:18,955 --> 01:10:21,867
I make something impossible,
and they rip it away from me,

895
01:10:21,955 --> 01:10:24,241
so I do it again and they do it again.

896
01:10:24,330 --> 01:10:26,571
And again. And again.

897
01:10:28,996 --> 01:10:30,827
This isn't like everything else.

898
01:10:32,580 --> 01:10:34,286
This is everything else.

899
01:10:35,580 --> 01:10:39,448
Our future is not gonna be paved
with bricks but with copper.

900
01:10:41,330 --> 01:10:45,403
Automation, transportation, communication,
and the man that controls that current

901
01:10:45,496 --> 01:10:47,452
controls that future.

902
01:10:48,621 --> 01:10:50,577
But you know Westinghouse is right.

903
01:10:52,288 --> 01:10:54,279
You don't actually believe
that a few accidents

904
01:10:54,371 --> 01:10:56,282
rule out the viability of his current.

905
01:10:56,371 --> 01:10:58,514
- You just don't want to lose.
- I have merely amplified

906
01:10:58,538 --> 01:11:00,620
what no one else
was willing to take seriously.

907
01:11:00,705 --> 01:11:03,037
No, what you did was run him over
with a 12-ton train.

908
01:11:03,121 --> 01:11:05,431
Oh, well, he's the one
that's supposed to only make brakes,

909
01:11:05,455 --> 01:11:07,446
so, who's to blame here?

910
01:11:10,121 --> 01:11:12,282
Switch tonight, and you win.

911
01:11:12,371 --> 01:11:14,453
His current kills people.

912
01:11:14,538 --> 01:11:15,903
Only because you said it will!

913
01:11:15,996 --> 01:11:18,783
Listen, I either stop complaining
about the scavengers in my garden

914
01:11:18,871 --> 01:11:22,409
or build a wall so damn high that people
will never even dare to scale it.

915
01:11:22,496 --> 01:11:24,327
You are the smartest man I know.

916
01:11:24,413 --> 01:11:27,655
Beyond building miracles out of thin air,

917
01:11:27,746 --> 01:11:30,158
I was most impressed by your principles.

918
01:11:32,121 --> 01:11:35,488
You didn't invent the incandescent.
People just think you did.

919
01:11:42,788 --> 01:11:47,578
Let me welcome you to the reality
of how things come into existence.

920
01:11:47,663 --> 01:11:50,700
We all contribute.
That's what invention is.

921
01:11:50,788 --> 01:11:54,576
The salt. The grain. The heat. The heart.

922
01:11:54,663 --> 01:11:58,201
But only one man makes the bread rise.

923
01:12:00,163 --> 01:12:02,700
That's the one that puts it all together

924
01:12:02,788 --> 01:12:05,700
and makes it taste so damn good
that people will go out there

925
01:12:05,788 --> 01:12:10,031
and hand over their hard-won dollars
to buy it.

926
01:12:10,121 --> 01:12:13,113
Mr. Edison, I want you to succeed. I do.

927
01:12:15,413 --> 01:12:18,405
But you have to switch tonight,
or you'll die as PT Barnum

928
01:12:18,496 --> 01:12:20,452
rather than Sir Isaac Newton.

929
01:12:45,205 --> 01:12:47,662
Though he may be unfamiliar to you,

930
01:12:47,746 --> 01:12:51,534
his studies have demonstrated
an understanding of electrical matters

931
01:12:51,621 --> 01:12:55,614
unlike anyone I have ever known,
with respect to the assembled.

932
01:12:55,705 --> 01:12:59,243
Gentlemen and lady, Nikola Tesla.

933
01:13:02,705 --> 01:13:05,242
Straight to our ultimate question,

934
01:13:05,996 --> 01:13:07,486
yes or no-...

935
01:13:08,330 --> 01:13:11,037
Can alternating currents operate a motor?

936
01:13:12,788 --> 01:13:14,028
Yes.

937
01:13:15,705 --> 01:13:17,821
Now anyone who builds
an alternating system

938
01:13:17,913 --> 01:13:21,326
will be able to do what Edison can
for only a third of the cost.

939
01:13:21,413 --> 01:13:23,654
In figure two of my polyphase system,
the armature coils

940
01:13:23,746 --> 01:13:25,611
are shown in a more advanced position.

941
01:13:25,705 --> 01:13:27,912
2-A illustrates the corresponding
magnetic condition...

942
01:13:27,996 --> 01:13:29,931
Synchronous motor obtained
by winding a laminated ring

943
01:13:29,955 --> 01:13:31,264
provided with pole projections...

944
01:13:31,288 --> 01:13:33,119
The induction is of an ideal character,

945
01:13:33,205 --> 01:13:35,571
being always maintained
at its maximum action.

946
01:13:35,663 --> 01:13:39,155
Mr. Tesla, have you actually built
the motor to test your theories?

947
01:13:39,246 --> 01:13:42,158
But they are not theories.
No, I have not built it.

948
01:13:42,246 --> 01:13:44,111
But that would prove your beliefs.

949
01:13:44,205 --> 01:13:47,038
But they are not beliefs,
and it is absolutely immaterial to me

950
01:13:47,121 --> 01:13:49,112
whether I run the motor in my mind
or in a shop,

951
01:13:49,205 --> 01:13:52,038
for I have built it already
in my imagination, and it is perfect.

952
01:13:52,121 --> 01:13:54,362
- Are you serious?
- Almost always.

953
01:14:03,746 --> 01:14:06,237
Hello. I'm George Westinghouse.

954
01:14:16,330 --> 01:14:18,036
- George Westinghouse?
- Mm-hmm.

955
01:14:18,121 --> 01:14:20,828
An engine that compresses air into a tank

956
01:14:20,913 --> 01:14:23,985
which is taken via pipe
to each brake on the train,

957
01:14:24,080 --> 01:14:26,366
allowing them to operate simultaneously.

958
01:14:30,038 --> 01:14:31,244
Thank you.

959
01:14:39,621 --> 01:14:40,861
Please.

960
01:14:56,413 --> 01:14:58,995
I think this entire room
is slanted two degrees.

961
01:15:03,288 --> 01:15:07,236
I sincerely appreciate you
taking the time to meet with me.

962
01:15:07,330 --> 01:15:09,696
Are-Are you going somewhere?

963
01:15:21,330 --> 01:15:22,365
Oh.

964
01:15:24,288 --> 01:15:26,529
- This is it?
- It's Niagara Falls.

965
01:15:26,621 --> 01:15:27,781
Yeah.

966
01:15:27,871 --> 01:15:30,863
And ever since my school days,
I have pictured in my imagination

967
01:15:30,955 --> 01:15:33,287
a big wheel spinning out lightning.

968
01:15:34,955 --> 01:15:38,197
Did you know that when I first came
to this country, I worked for Mr. Edison?

969
01:15:38,288 --> 01:15:40,119
- I did not.
- Tea?

970
01:15:40,205 --> 01:15:41,741
Sure.

971
01:15:42,580 --> 01:15:45,492
I fixed two of his DC generators
in one night,

972
01:15:45,580 --> 01:15:47,696
and he called me a damn good man.

973
01:15:48,788 --> 01:15:50,904
So, why did he not treat me that way?

974
01:15:50,996 --> 01:15:54,159
I quit.
Tried my own company and was deceived.

975
01:15:54,246 --> 01:15:56,532
Who was I? Some immigrant.

976
01:15:57,580 --> 01:16:00,242
SO I TOOK THE ONLYJOB I COULD fiND:
Digging a ditch.

977
01:16:01,580 --> 01:16:05,118
The men laughed at my fine clothes,
but at the end of the day, I had $2.

978
01:16:08,121 --> 01:16:10,533
What was the ditch to be used for?

979
01:16:11,538 --> 01:16:13,278
Edison Electric.

980
01:16:14,621 --> 01:16:16,486
It felt like digging my own grave.

981
01:16:18,121 --> 01:16:22,069
If Mr. Edison succeeds, he will set us
back so far, we may never recover.

982
01:16:22,163 --> 01:16:24,495
The Fair must be alternating.

983
01:16:24,580 --> 01:16:26,161
It must be my motor.

984
01:16:26,871 --> 01:16:29,613
I have watched as the world talks
of Chicago as a symbol,

985
01:16:29,705 --> 01:16:31,070
a City of Light.

986
01:16:31,913 --> 01:16:35,076
All cities will have light
in your lifetime,

987
01:16:35,163 --> 01:16:39,702
but harnessing the power of Niagara,
that is to see our future.

988
01:16:39,788 --> 01:16:43,451
The Falls? I'm here to talk about Chicago.

989
01:16:43,538 --> 01:16:44,948
Think beyond Chicago.

990
01:16:45,038 --> 01:16:48,735
Energy is as fundamental
as food, as water, as air.

991
01:16:48,830 --> 01:16:51,947
You can... You cannot say
that only those with money can eat

992
01:16:52,038 --> 01:16:53,744
or can breathe.

993
01:16:53,830 --> 01:16:55,639
Yes, the Falls will light up
the Eastern Seaboard.

994
01:16:55,663 --> 01:16:58,556
Yes, there is a great fortune to be made,
and I covet a very nice walking stick

995
01:16:58,580 --> 01:17:00,912
I saw on 63rd and Madison,
but Niagara is the proof

996
01:17:00,996 --> 01:17:03,032
that one day we may detach power
from profit.

997
01:17:03,121 --> 01:17:05,658
- That is how you truly win.
- Mm.

998
01:17:06,580 --> 01:17:10,744
- How do I know you will not cheat me?
- Well, you don't.

999
01:17:13,288 --> 01:17:16,030
But the fact is, Mr. Tesla,
I need your motor.

1000
01:17:16,121 --> 01:17:19,568
I may be able to light up the Fair,
but I still can't move a machine.

1001
01:17:19,663 --> 01:17:23,076
If we cannot reach an agreement today,
my company will die

1002
01:17:23,163 --> 01:17:25,028
right here in your hotel room.

1003
01:17:27,538 --> 01:17:31,281
But if it does perish, so might your dream
of harnessing power from Niagara.

1004
01:17:35,746 --> 01:17:37,737
So, do we have a deal?

1005
01:17:39,621 --> 01:17:40,986
Five thousand.

1006
01:17:48,746 --> 01:17:50,031
One thousand.

1007
01:18:02,038 --> 01:18:03,073
Yeah.

1008
01:18:05,830 --> 01:18:07,912
I'll give you $2.50...

1009
01:18:12,371 --> 01:18:13,736
per horsepower.

1010
01:18:15,246 --> 01:18:19,068
I'm no genius myself,
but that should be millions.

1011
01:18:21,996 --> 01:18:24,362
May I treat you to dinner at Delmonico's?

1012
01:18:25,788 --> 01:18:27,699
All right, Mr. Tesla, time to go.

1013
01:18:27,788 --> 01:18:31,108
- No, I will not leave your slanted room.
- He hasn't paid his bill in over a month.

1014
01:18:31,163 --> 01:18:34,451
Well, how much would it cost
to keep him here for the year?

1015
01:18:39,413 --> 01:18:42,450
I need to shed 300 men
from the gas company.

1016
01:18:45,705 --> 01:18:47,787
There's no way around it.

1017
01:18:48,580 --> 01:18:51,380
So we pay their salaries
and move them to the electricity.

1018
01:18:51,455 --> 01:18:53,446
We can't keep doing this.

1019
01:18:54,496 --> 01:18:56,703
If we win, we won't have to.

1020
01:18:58,746 --> 01:19:00,577
You have truth on your side.

1021
01:19:02,788 --> 01:19:06,906
And whatever happens, you'll know
you never did anything but play fair.

1022
01:19:18,871 --> 01:19:20,486
I stole the letters

1023
01:19:20,580 --> 01:19:22,946
linking Edison to the death chair.

1024
01:19:24,330 --> 01:19:26,662
I gave them to the papers to smudge him.

1025
01:19:29,413 --> 01:19:31,278
I know you're disappointed in me.

1026
01:20:01,621 --> 01:20:03,452
What am I looking at here?

1027
01:20:03,538 --> 01:20:06,951
An 80-foot tall tower
covered with 16,000 Edison bulbs,

1028
01:20:07,038 --> 01:20:08,869
topped with an eight-foot lighthouse.

1029
01:20:08,955 --> 01:20:11,162
That signals to the world
that we are the victors.

1030
01:20:11,246 --> 01:20:13,282
Otherwise,
how will people know that we won?

1031
01:20:13,996 --> 01:20:15,327
It's an idol.

1032
01:20:16,246 --> 01:20:17,952
It's a... signature.

1033
01:20:19,371 --> 01:20:22,693
And you'll get something that no one's
ever received from Thomas Edison before.

1034
01:20:22,788 --> 01:20:24,995
- Oh, yes? What's that?
- An apology.

1035
01:20:25,080 --> 01:20:29,119
I admit that spending has been,
well, more than anticipated,

1036
01:20:29,205 --> 01:20:32,368
but now, more than ever,
it's important you must push through.

1037
01:20:32,455 --> 01:20:36,243
Whatever Westinghouse is bidding
for the Fair, we... you must bid more.

1038
01:20:36,330 --> 01:20:37,536
I must.

1039
01:20:38,996 --> 01:20:40,031
"Must."

1040
01:20:42,288 --> 01:20:43,698
Who's Nikola Tesla?

1041
01:20:46,705 --> 01:20:47,820
What about him?

1042
01:20:47,913 --> 01:20:50,325
Well, he gave a talk at Columbia.

1043
01:20:50,413 --> 01:20:54,611
Word is, the Serb is building Westinghouse
a polyphase motor.

1044
01:20:55,205 --> 01:20:59,027
Light and power.
You can do both. He now may as well.

1045
01:20:59,121 --> 01:21:01,806
Who even knows how long it'll take them
to build a functioning model...

1046
01:21:01,830 --> 01:21:05,072
As of this morning,
you have ceded, I have here,

1047
01:21:05,163 --> 01:21:07,620
nine more cities to Westinghouse.

1048
01:21:07,705 --> 01:21:09,821
So, here's what's happening.

1049
01:21:10,871 --> 01:21:14,944
I am merging Edison Electric
with some of the other ankle-biters.

1050
01:21:15,413 --> 01:21:17,404
You are out.

1051
01:21:18,330 --> 01:21:19,536
You know why.

1052
01:21:20,413 --> 01:21:23,951
And I'm happy to tell you, if you require
this moment to be even more unpleasant.

1053
01:21:24,038 --> 01:21:26,245
You will receive stock,

1054
01:21:26,330 --> 01:21:28,696
and you will retain a seat on the board.

1055
01:21:35,371 --> 01:21:36,736
Who's gonna present? You?

1056
01:21:36,830 --> 01:21:39,446
- Good God, no.
- You tell me now?

1057
01:21:39,538 --> 01:21:41,639
I was here. I thought you deserved
to hear it face-to-face.

1058
01:21:41,663 --> 01:21:44,780
No, you didn't.
You just wanted to waste my time

1059
01:21:44,871 --> 01:21:46,987
and get me to sign autographs
for children.

1060
01:21:48,121 --> 01:21:50,264
- What are you going to call it then?
- That's your concern?

1061
01:21:50,288 --> 01:21:51,949
Edison Electric. It has to be.

1062
01:21:52,038 --> 01:21:55,530
Edison and electricity are synonymous,
Morgan. The bulb...

1063
01:21:55,621 --> 01:21:58,533
I do not attach a losing name
to a fledgling enterprise.

1064
01:21:58,621 --> 01:22:00,987
Now that your letters have leaked,
you've lost credibility.

1065
01:22:01,080 --> 01:22:02,200
- So, what is it?
- The name?

1066
01:22:02,246 --> 01:22:03,861
Yes, the goddamn name!

1067
01:22:03,955 --> 01:22:06,742
The contractjust says General Electric,
but I'll think of something.

1068
01:22:06,830 --> 01:22:07,945
I can be creative too.

1069
01:22:13,621 --> 01:22:14,701
Yeah.

1070
01:22:17,538 --> 01:22:18,618
Mr. lnsull.

1071
01:22:20,955 --> 01:22:22,070
A moment.

1072
01:23:01,371 --> 01:23:04,329
He said they'd keep your name attached
as long as you didn't pursue action

1073
01:23:04,413 --> 01:23:06,574
or speak negatively to the press
about the merger.

1074
01:23:06,663 --> 01:23:07,994
What did he offer you?

1075
01:23:09,121 --> 01:23:11,081
- Tell me.
- Vice president, but I turned it down.

1076
01:23:11,121 --> 01:23:12,281
- You should take it.
- Why?

1077
01:23:12,371 --> 01:23:14,264
Alternating current...
What's the transmission voltage?

1078
01:23:14,288 --> 01:23:15,494
230,000 volts.

1079
01:23:15,580 --> 01:23:17,320
What's the filament on a 12,000-hour lamp?

1080
01:23:17,413 --> 01:23:19,514
- Carbonized Japanese bamboo.
- What do I eat for breakfast?

1081
01:23:19,538 --> 01:23:20,764
- Pie.
- So, what's the surprise?

1082
01:23:20,788 --> 01:23:23,621
Of course he needs you.
You're me, but a human being.

1083
01:23:32,621 --> 01:23:34,282
Look around the room.

1084
01:23:34,371 --> 01:23:35,781
- Hmm?
- Who's missing?

1085
01:23:37,871 --> 01:23:41,068
Edison General Electric Company, please.

1086
01:23:41,163 --> 01:23:42,903
General Electric?

1087
01:23:42,996 --> 01:23:45,612
- Edison General Electric Company.
- Yes.

1088
01:23:45,705 --> 01:23:47,536
Ah!

1089
01:24:00,746 --> 01:24:01,986
He's 12.

1090
01:24:02,080 --> 01:24:05,618
Mr. Insull, these are
the committee members of...

1091
01:24:05,705 --> 01:24:08,242
Listen closely.
Focus on the quality of the light.

1092
01:24:08,330 --> 01:24:10,412
I don't care what the courts say.

1093
01:24:10,496 --> 01:24:12,077
Westinghouse ripped off my bulbs,

1094
01:24:12,163 --> 01:24:14,779
and the good news for you
is he did a terrible job.

1095
01:24:14,871 --> 01:24:18,068
They are outdoor bulbs,
so they have a life of about two hours.

1096
01:24:18,163 --> 01:24:20,074
So focus on the replacement time.

1097
01:24:21,163 --> 01:24:24,826
Talk about the superiority of ours,
as if there's no competition.

1098
01:24:25,413 --> 01:24:27,950
Use terms like "standard," "purest,"

1099
01:24:28,038 --> 01:24:30,029
"the most beautiful light," et cetera.

1100
01:24:30,121 --> 01:24:32,764
Find out what kind of men they are.
There are really only two types.

1101
01:24:32,788 --> 01:24:36,201
The first believe themselves to be
practical, but they're secret dreamers.

1102
01:24:36,288 --> 01:24:38,199
They're the ones who'll take the risks.

1103
01:24:38,288 --> 01:24:40,700
The second, well, they'll smile
and thank you for the show,

1104
01:24:40,788 --> 01:24:42,494
but they'll vote with their wallets.

1105
01:24:42,580 --> 01:24:46,368
Unless Westinghouse is mortgaging
everything he's worth on this bid,

1106
01:24:46,455 --> 01:24:48,411
Morgan has you in good stead
with the money men.

1107
01:24:48,496 --> 01:24:51,112
So your only real job
is to look the dreamers in the eye

1108
01:24:51,205 --> 01:24:52,911
and promise them magic.

1109
01:24:52,996 --> 01:24:56,033
Now, explain back to me everything
that you remember about a parallel

1110
01:24:56,121 --> 01:24:58,801
and series of electric circuits
using none of the words I just said.

1111
01:25:00,496 --> 01:25:03,158
Though I am young,
I am an expert in these matters,

1112
01:25:03,246 --> 01:25:06,238
rivaled only really by Mr. Edison himself.

1113
01:25:06,330 --> 01:25:09,037
Should you choose Westinghouse, then...

1114
01:25:09,121 --> 01:25:11,612
then yes, there is a possibility

1115
01:25:11,705 --> 01:25:14,742
you'll be putting in jeopardy
the lives of 28 million people.

1116
01:25:15,996 --> 01:25:19,909
Even if Westinghouse were to make
even the smallest of errors,

1117
01:25:19,996 --> 01:25:22,237
unintentional, of course,

1118
01:25:22,330 --> 01:25:24,321
a visiting politician, a wife,

1119
01:25:24,413 --> 01:25:26,654
even a seven-year-old girl
may lean against a lamppost

1120
01:25:26,746 --> 01:25:28,657
and be struck dead immediately.

1121
01:25:29,330 --> 01:25:30,661
There you have it.

1122
01:25:30,746 --> 01:25:33,988
Mr. Westinghouse's brand of electricity
is fatal.

1123
01:25:34,080 --> 01:25:36,492
Thank you, Mr. lnsull.

1124
01:25:36,580 --> 01:25:38,161
Just to be clear, sir,

1125
01:25:38,246 --> 01:25:41,409
any electrical current
over 200 milliamperes can be deadly.

1126
01:25:41,496 --> 01:25:42,906
Even yours?

1127
01:25:50,871 --> 01:25:52,953
Mr. Westinghouse,
these are the committee members.

1128
01:25:53,038 --> 01:25:54,778
OF GROUNDS AND BUILDINGS:

1129
01:25:54,871 --> 01:25:57,453
Charles Schwab, Craig Cannon,

1130
01:25:57,538 --> 01:25:59,654
- Mayor Cregier, of course.
- Oh, of course.

1131
01:25:59,746 --> 01:26:02,203
Victor Lawson of the Chicago Daily News,

1132
01:26:02,288 --> 01:26:04,620
and the Honorable Judge Tree.

1133
01:26:04,705 --> 01:26:06,115
I'm Daniel Burnham.

1134
01:26:06,205 --> 01:26:10,403
Respectfully, we ask that you please
keep your remarks to one hour.

1135
01:26:10,496 --> 01:26:12,157
That won't be necessary.

1136
01:26:12,871 --> 01:26:15,112
- Here you go. Sir.
- Thank you.

1137
01:26:16,705 --> 01:26:17,865
Hmm.

1138
01:26:20,496 --> 01:26:22,236
My bid.

1139
01:26:22,330 --> 01:26:24,036
These are all your figures?

1140
01:26:24,121 --> 01:26:26,362
Yes, sir. Independent estimates.

1141
01:26:26,455 --> 01:26:29,777
Before we, uh,
get into the messy business,

1142
01:26:29,871 --> 01:26:32,988
let us begin
with this most general question:

1143
01:26:33,080 --> 01:26:37,870
Why should we grant Westinghouse Electric
the contract for the World's Fair?

1144
01:26:37,955 --> 01:26:42,619
Well, I guess because
our system works significantly better,

1145
01:26:42,705 --> 01:26:43,865
and, uh...

1146
01:26:46,205 --> 01:26:49,242
because our system
is significantly cheaper.

1147
01:26:54,413 --> 01:26:57,280
Mr. Schwab, Mr. Higinbotham, Mr. Cannon,

1148
01:26:57,371 --> 01:27:00,568
Mayor Cregier, Mr. Lawson, Judge Tree,

1149
01:27:00,663 --> 01:27:01,948
and Mr. Burnham,

1150
01:27:02,705 --> 01:27:05,617
thank you very much for your time
and your consideration.

1151
01:27:19,538 --> 01:27:21,870
Financially, it's clear.
We just take the better bid.

1152
01:27:21,955 --> 01:27:24,867
- Look, Westinghouse is dangerous.
- Potentially dangerous.

1153
01:27:24,955 --> 01:27:26,946
You even printed it in your own paper.

1154
01:27:27,038 --> 01:27:30,451
Alternating will be used
to kill that man in Buffalo.

1155
01:27:42,705 --> 01:27:44,491
They both light up lights, right?

1156
01:27:44,580 --> 01:27:47,572
Westinghouse saves us some money.
Thomas Edison sells tickets.

1157
01:27:51,038 --> 01:27:53,871
What I wouldn't give to flip through that.

1158
01:27:53,955 --> 01:27:56,617
It's like a handbook
to the future, isn't it?

1159
01:28:00,496 --> 01:28:03,329
- We need a clear majority, gentlemen.
- Don't you have stock in GE?

1160
01:28:03,413 --> 01:28:04,778
That's irrelevant.

1161
01:28:06,330 --> 01:28:09,242
No one has ever done
what you have done for me.

1162
01:28:09,330 --> 01:28:12,777
The value of something
isn't what someone's willing to pay,

1163
01:28:12,871 --> 01:28:16,034
but the value of something
is what it contributes.

1164
01:28:16,121 --> 01:28:19,739
When we vote again, Burnham,
you can telephone the winner tonight.

1165
01:28:24,288 --> 01:28:26,779
Is it true you were born
during a lightning storm?

1166
01:28:27,871 --> 01:28:29,486
It is true.

1167
01:28:31,663 --> 01:28:34,075
All right. Tell me one thing in that book.

1168
01:28:36,455 --> 01:28:39,572
Look, you and Mr. Edison, you spend
all your time on either end of the system,

1169
01:28:39,663 --> 01:28:41,574
the dynamos and the lamps.

1170
01:28:41,663 --> 01:28:43,745
But what about what is in between?

1171
01:28:43,830 --> 01:28:45,240
- The wires?
- Mm.

1172
01:28:46,330 --> 01:28:49,037
Do we need them?

1173
01:29:04,246 --> 01:29:08,239
The problem is, despite
all the advantages of the Remington...

1174
01:29:12,663 --> 01:29:16,076
it doesn't fix the fact that
you just dampened the gunpowder.

1175
01:29:48,080 --> 01:29:49,616
What's this?

1176
01:29:52,496 --> 01:29:56,114
This is gonna do for the eye
what the phonograph did for the ear.

1177
01:30:02,538 --> 01:30:03,618
Dot?

1178
01:30:20,205 --> 01:30:21,240
Again.

1179
01:30:24,621 --> 01:30:25,701
Again!

1180
01:31:58,496 --> 01:32:00,407
Do you have any final words?

1181
01:32:02,705 --> 01:32:05,071
I believe I'm going to a better place.

1182
01:32:07,455 --> 01:32:08,865
Goodbye, William.

1183
01:32:17,413 --> 01:32:20,860
We live in a higher civilization...

1184
01:32:21,830 --> 01:32:23,286
from this day.

1185
01:33:41,663 --> 01:33:45,076
"An awful spectacle,
far worse than hanging."

1186
01:33:45,163 --> 01:33:49,281
'They would have done better with an ax.'

1187
01:33:49,371 --> 01:33:51,487
Sizzling sound. A billow of smoke

1188
01:33:51,580 --> 01:33:53,912
"that filled the room
with the odor of burning hair."

1189
01:33:55,413 --> 01:33:57,495
Well, at least it happened to a murderer.

1190
01:33:59,371 --> 01:34:01,987
At least
they'll never use it again to kill anyone.

1191
01:34:09,580 --> 01:34:11,571
Soon all these people
will have electric light,

1192
01:34:11,663 --> 01:34:13,949
and no one will even remember
it ever happened.

1193
01:34:15,496 --> 01:34:17,737
I have books so full of ideas

1194
01:34:17,830 --> 01:34:20,902
it would take me more than 12 lifetimes
to execute them.

1195
01:34:22,413 --> 01:34:24,779
So let the man have his fair
and waterfall.

1196
01:34:30,080 --> 01:34:31,695
Well, for what's it's worth,

1197
01:34:32,246 --> 01:34:35,784
I'd much rather have worked for you
than Westinghouse any day.

1198
01:34:35,871 --> 01:34:37,031
Why is that?

1199
01:34:37,955 --> 01:34:40,241
Well, I wouldn't have had as much fun,
would I?

1200
01:35:41,371 --> 01:35:43,487
Have you seen much of the fair?

1201
01:35:43,580 --> 01:35:46,822
- A Muybridge lecture, Little Egypt.
- Oh, the dancer.

1202
01:35:46,913 --> 01:35:48,278
- You saw her?
- No.

1203
01:35:49,163 --> 01:35:52,280
Well, she was... If you get the time.

1204
01:35:53,205 --> 01:35:54,240
Hmm.

1205
01:35:59,246 --> 01:36:01,908
Don't you think
a fence is a unique creation?

1206
01:36:03,705 --> 01:36:06,742
Your neighbor puts one up,
and suddenly one becomes two.

1207
01:36:07,663 --> 01:36:11,076
You also have a fence.
There's only one problem.

1208
01:36:11,163 --> 01:36:14,405
You see, one person
on one side of the fence designed it,

1209
01:36:14,496 --> 01:36:16,703
one person on one side built it,

1210
01:36:16,788 --> 01:36:18,949
and one person paid for it,

1211
01:36:19,038 --> 01:36:22,781
and yet the other person receives
a fine, free fence.

1212
01:36:25,496 --> 01:36:27,452
I didn't take your ideas.

1213
01:36:28,288 --> 01:36:29,528
Mr. Edison?

1214
01:36:30,788 --> 01:36:31,823
Sure.

1215
01:36:33,663 --> 01:36:34,778
Thank you.

1216
01:36:35,788 --> 01:36:38,905
- I was wondering about one thing.
- Oh, I'm sure there were many.

1217
01:36:38,996 --> 01:36:42,864
I was gonna invite you to dinner again,

1218
01:36:42,955 --> 01:36:45,367
but I suppose now
is as good a time as any.

1219
01:36:45,455 --> 01:36:46,931
You want to know
what was in the 13-hour bulb?

1220
01:36:46,955 --> 01:36:49,116
- I know how it works.
- Yeah, I know you do.

1221
01:36:49,205 --> 01:36:51,196
I only wondered what it felt like.

1222
01:36:53,246 --> 01:36:54,611
- Pardon?
- The bulb.

1223
01:36:55,621 --> 01:36:56,986
When you knew.

1224
01:36:57,538 --> 01:36:59,904
What was the feeling in that moment?

1225
01:37:08,330 --> 01:37:09,945
I can't tell you. I mean...

1226
01:37:11,788 --> 01:37:16,487
It's impossible to describe the feeling
because it was impossible.

1227
01:37:17,413 --> 01:37:20,371
Years of work.
Ten thousand different filaments.

1228
01:37:20,871 --> 01:37:23,157
When the thread went in the bulb,
as usual,

1229
01:37:23,246 --> 01:37:26,158
we placed our bets
and the generator sputtered to life

1230
01:37:26,246 --> 01:37:29,989
and the ball began to glow, we didn't
expect anything but another failure.

1231
01:37:32,121 --> 01:37:34,077
Then something started to happen.

1232
01:37:37,746 --> 01:37:40,533
See, our best filament
only lasted ten minutes,

1233
01:37:41,246 --> 01:37:44,363
and this fluke was rounding 20,

1234
01:37:44,455 --> 01:37:46,616
so people started to chatter.

1235
01:37:46,705 --> 01:37:50,493
And 30 minutes, 40 minutes,
an hour, two hours.

1236
01:37:50,580 --> 01:37:52,696
Then people started to shout.

1237
01:37:52,788 --> 01:37:55,450
And remember,
we hadn't got past ten minutes.

1238
01:37:56,246 --> 01:37:59,534
The boys were climbing up the walls,
tearing their hair out, and...

1239
01:38:01,371 --> 01:38:03,236
because it was impossible.

1240
01:38:04,288 --> 01:38:07,655
Seven hours. Eight hours. Nine.

1241
01:38:09,163 --> 01:38:10,994
We were silent when we hit ten.

1242
01:38:13,330 --> 01:38:15,696
Just sat around that glowing bubble,

1243
01:38:15,788 --> 01:38:18,860
drunk on our own magic,
staring at it like it...

1244
01:38:18,955 --> 01:38:21,992
I don't know, like it was the baby Jesus
playing Mozart.

1245
01:38:25,663 --> 01:38:28,985
After 13 and a half hours,
the glass cracked, and I knew it.

1246
01:38:31,330 --> 01:38:33,195
The world would never be the same.

1247
01:38:35,330 --> 01:38:38,402
I'm working on something now,
something so new that...

1248
01:38:40,038 --> 01:38:43,781
people will forget that my name
was ever associated with electricity.

1249
01:38:43,871 --> 01:38:45,987
I wonder if you know what it is yet.

1250
01:38:52,163 --> 01:38:54,245
You know, I think the solution is...

1251
01:38:54,913 --> 01:38:56,949
to divide the cost of the fence.

1252
01:38:59,371 --> 01:39:02,488
Or you cannot build a fence at all.

1253
01:39:05,371 --> 01:39:07,407
Your garden would be twice as big.

1254
01:39:08,163 --> 01:39:10,154
Wouldn't it, Tom?

1255
01:39:17,621 --> 01:39:19,577
If nothing else, a pleasure.

1256
01:39:21,830 --> 01:39:23,366
Enjoy the fair, George.

1257
01:39:41,455 --> 01:39:45,152
We build monuments to speak
to the future, to say, "We were here."

1258
01:39:46,871 --> 01:39:48,327
"We have lived."

1259
01:39:49,663 --> 01:39:53,406
A true legacy
isn't what we build up to the heavens

1260
01:39:53,496 --> 01:39:55,578
or carve deep into stone.

1261
01:39:56,746 --> 01:39:58,907
Rocks will crumble,

1262
01:39:58,996 --> 01:40:00,611
paper disintegrates,

1263
01:40:05,121 --> 01:40:08,079
Only that
which isn't in the physical realm

1264
01:40:08,163 --> 01:40:10,700
and reaches in both directions
can be eternal.

1265
01:40:12,538 --> 01:40:13,948
Our ideas.

1266
01:40:15,913 --> 01:40:17,904
They are what we leave behind.

1267
01:40:19,371 --> 01:40:21,783
And only they
are what can push us forward.

